<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08077e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08077e">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08077e"> 77(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> to darkle <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n08077e"><li>FW 404.01 </li><li><a href="../../flex/pA/lexpA.htm#n08077e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/pA/l39pA.htm#n08077e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n08077e">MS BL 47482b-9</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:019 <a name="pA1d" href="../../ff/fdra/pda.htm#pA1d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/p/pA1d.htm#n08077e">Draft: III&sect;1A.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The adverbs <i>sideling</i>, <i>groveling</i> and <i>darkling</i> were originally formed by means of the adverbial ending <i>-ling</i>, but in such phrases as <i>he walks sideling</i>, <i>he lies groveling</i>, etc., they looked exactly like participles in <i>-ing</i>, and the consequence was that the new verbs to <i>sidle</i>, to <i>grovel</i>, and to <i>darkle</i> were derived from them by the subtraction of <i>-ing</i>. <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 170</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
